00:19:35,000 --> 00:19:39,000
which is generating hydrogen for outright sale of the gas.

207
00:19:39,000 --> 00:19:46,000
The hydrogen refueling system that we have developed is based on the reformation of natural gas, reacting with water.

208
00:19:46,000 --> 00:19:50,000
There's a lot of critics of this approach because we're using a carbon-based fuel.

209
00:19:50,000 --> 00:19:57,000
While it's not totally carbon-free, it's an obvious choice as a part of the roadmap to carbon reduction.

210
00:19:58,000 --> 00:20:03,000
The stack on top you see is a commercially available stack that goes into our power-edge systems.

211
00:20:03,000 --> 00:20:08,000
These are systems that are provided to the material handling market as battery replacements.

212
00:20:08,000 --> 00:20:12,000
What's intended for industrial heavy-duty industrial applications.

213
00:20:12,000 --> 00:20:19,000
The real advantage of fuel cells over other power plant type technologies is they are inherently scalable.

214
00:20:19,000 --> 00:20:24,000
So if I need a stack of just one kilowatt, there it is.

215
00:20:24,000 --> 00:20:28,000
If I need this stack to be 90 kilowatts, I simply add cells to it.

216
00:20:28,000 --> 00:20:33,000
In terms of the prime power plant, the prime energy converter, it's real, it's today, we're doing it.

217
00:20:33,000 --> 00:20:37,000
They're ready, they're reliable, we're deploying them in fork trucks.

218
00:20:37,000 --> 00:20:42,000
The fork truck market is an ideal proving ground because it's a vehicle that's already electrified.

219
00:20:42,000 --> 00:20:49,000
It already uses batteries and we're proving that the fuel cell has value in displacing batteries in that application.

220
00:20:49,000 --> 00:20:57,000
This system is designed so that the user can push out the lead acid battery, put in our system and the truck doesn't know the difference.

221
00:20:57,000 --> 00:21:03,000
It's a hybrid system which has, instead of the gasoline-powered engine, we have a fuel cell engine,

222
00:21:03,000 --> 00:21:10,000
which actually is one of the nice points about fuel cells with the growth of hybrid technology in over-the-road vehicles.

223
00:21:10,000 --> 00:21:15,000
You can very easily see how you could take the internal combustion engine out and put a fuel cell in.

224
00:21:15,000 --> 00:21:22,000
In the traditional power supply system for electric forklifts, you have big racks and racks of lead acid batteries.

225
00:21:22,000 --> 00:21:29,000
For every truck you have up to three batteries and when the battery dies, you have to take it to a specialized machine

226
00:21:29,000 --> 00:21:33,000
that pulls the battery out, puts it up on a rack to be charged and puts a new battery in.

227
00:21:33,000 --> 00:21:34,000
All this is very time intensive.

228
00:21:34,000 --> 00:21:38,000
A battery takes eight hours to charge and eight hours to cool.

229
00:21:38,000 --> 00:21:40,000
This system takes about two minutes to refuel.

230
00:21:40,000 --> 00:21:42,000
This is a fuel cell stack.

231
00:21:42,000 --> 00:21:46,000
This is what I call the dry end of the system because there's no water.

232
00:21:46,000 --> 00:21:48,000
This is the wet end.

233
00:21:48,000 --> 00:21:51,000
There's a condenser here for managing heat and water.

234
00:21:51,000 --> 00:21:54,000
So as a fuel cell runs, it creates water.

235
00:21:54,000 --> 00:21:59,000
This manages the water to keep it from getting too high or too low and also rejects the heat.

236
00:21:59,000 --> 00:22:06,000
Also in here we have the fuel handling components that take the very high pressure from the tank and step it down.

237
00:22:06,000 --> 00:22:12,000
There's an onboard computer which allows the fuel cell system to provide you with intelligent power.

238
00:22:12,000 --> 00:22:14,000
A lead acid battery is just a dumb battery.

239
00:22:14,000 --> 00:22:18,000
It can't tell you anything about how healthy it is or how productive the operator is

240
00:22:18,000 --> 00:22:22,000
and what it will do is it will just slowly drain down in performance over the course of the shift

241
00:22:22,000 --> 00:22:24,000
just like a flashlight that's going dim.

242
00:22:24,000 --> 00:22:27,000
What you find with these is you'll have consistent power.

243
00:22:27,000 --> 00:22:36,000
When you talk about family cars or SUVs, batteries will be too heavy and too bulky to be deployed and too expensive.

244
00:22:36,000 --> 00:22:44,000
To put a battery in a mini van today, you would have to add about 450 pounds.

245
00:22:44,000 --> 00:22:48,000
And that's carrying a gorilla inside your car.

246
00:22:48,000 --> 00:22:53,000
It's an invisible gorilla but nobody wants a gorilla in addition to the car you have.

247
00:22:53,000 --> 00:23:00,000
That's where the fuel cell will come in and will have the right substitute in that case.

248
00:23:07,000 --> 00:23:14,000
This is the world's first automated fuel cell assembly line.

249
00:23:14,000 --> 00:23:17,000
We can do a thousand cells a day.

250
00:23:17,000 --> 00:23:19,000
Some of our stacks require about 50 cells.

251
00:23:19,000 --> 00:23:26,000
The reason for doing the line is, again, we're competing in a market that we have to compete with batteries and generators.

252
00:23:26,000 --> 00:23:27,000
And how do we do this?

253
00:23:27,000 --> 00:23:33,000
One of the things that we found in order to compete in a world market is we can't have exotic materials.

254
00:23:33,000 --> 00:23:41,000
We figured out how we could design this in such a way that we could build it with robotics that are the same as the auto industry,

255
00:23:41,000 --> 00:23:43,000
that are the same in the computer industry.

256
00:23:43,000 --> 00:23:50,000
Not exotics, not the super titanium, it's not the stuff that is just very, very costly high expenses.

257
00:23:50,000 --> 00:23:54,000
But we found low-cost materials that we could go ahead and put these together with.

258
00:23:54,000 --> 00:24:00,000
Everything that is readily available wherever we need to to become a global competitor.

259
00:24:00,000 --> 00:24:04,000
What we're building today, we're actually finding those marks that we can go into.

260
00:24:04,000 --> 00:24:11,000
The telecom industry, the data centers, those backup supports that we need that would replace the battery or the generator.

261
00:24:11,000 --> 00:24:15,000
So right away, we're going to go ahead and drive to those newer markets.

262
00:24:15,000 --> 00:24:19,000
This happens to be a 1,000-watt system that we've created.

263
00:24:19,000 --> 00:24:21,000
This is a 5,000-watt system.

264
00:24:21,000 --> 00:24:23,000
We have communications.

265
00:24:23,000 --> 00:24:27,000
We can actually, from a remote distance, if the fuel gets to a certain level,

266
00:24:27,000 --> 00:24:32,000
we can go ahead and have this unit call the fuel provider and have them go ahead and say,

267
00:24:32,000 --> 00:24:36,000
hey, fuel's low, come and take care of it before the incident happens,

268
00:24:36,000 --> 00:24:40,000
before you start running this unit and all of a sudden you find out that you're out of fuel.

269
00:24:40,000 --> 00:24:46,000
And this is just conventional batteries that you see quite often in data centers and telecom systems.

270
00:24:46,000 --> 00:24:52,000
Just like any common generator, it takes, in some generators, it may take two, three minutes to come on.

271
00:24:52,000 --> 00:24:56,000
We can come on within about five seconds, three to five seconds.

272
00:24:56,000 --> 00:24:57,000
Or an instant.

273
00:24:57,000 --> 00:25:04,000
But in order not to lose that power, we bridge it with a small battery for a short period of time.

274
00:25:04,000 --> 00:25:05,000
I can demonstrate this.

275
00:25:05,000 --> 00:25:08,000
We turn on these really super bright lights here.

276
00:25:08,000 --> 00:25:12,000
And right now, the fuel cell is armed and it's watching the grid.

277
00:25:12,000 --> 00:25:16,000
And it's intelligent enough to see if the grid starts to drop.

278
00:25:16,000 --> 00:25:18,000
The fuel cell knows that it's time to come on.

279
00:25:18,000 --> 00:25:21,000
As soon as we shut off the power, the grid is there.

280
00:25:21,000 --> 00:25:24,000
The fuel cell's armed.

281
00:25:24,000 --> 00:25:27,000
Fuel cell immediately knew to come on because it lost the power.

282
00:25:27,000 --> 00:25:31,000
It no longer has any power, but you didn't see any blinks in the light whatsoever.

283
00:25:31,000 --> 00:25:32,000
Not one.

284
00:25:32,000 --> 00:25:36,000
There's all kinds of opportunities that are open to what the fuel cell has to offer.

285
00:25:36,000 --> 00:25:40,000
It's open for the imagination.

286
00:25:40,000 --> 00:25:43,000
This is a thousand watt system right here.

287
00:25:43,000 --> 00:25:45,000
It's a unit that we can use outdoors.

288
00:25:45,000 --> 00:25:49,000
This is the one that actually Governor Schwarzenegger used to light his Christmas tree every year.

289
00:25:49,000 --> 00:25:54,000
Normally a 60-foot Christmas tree that had at one time 5,000 watt light bulbs on it

290
00:25:54,000 --> 00:25:58,000
and consumed about 25,000 watts of power.

291
00:25:58,000 --> 00:26:01,000
We were able to come back through, talk to them about that,

292
00:26:01,000 --> 00:26:05,000
change their way of looking at it, put LED lights on this unit,

293
00:26:05,000 --> 00:26:11,000
ended up dropping the consumption from 25,000 watts down to 450 watts.

294
00:26:11,000 --> 00:26:16,000
And we were able to use it with a small little thousand watt fuel cell system that we have here.

295
00:26:16,000 --> 00:26:20,000
So every year he delights in the fact that he's running a Christmas tree

296
00:26:20,000 --> 00:26:25,000
cost-effectively and showing that there's other alternatives to power.

297
00:26:25,000 --> 00:26:29,000
This is green and that's the great and wonderful thing about this is

298
00:26:29,000 --> 00:26:37,000
it's zero pollution, low noise, plus a tremendous amount of energy and a very small package.

299
00:26:37,000 --> 00:26:38,000
These are real.

300
00:26:38,000 --> 00:26:42,000
These are pieces of equipment we're going to see being used on a daily basis.

301
00:26:42,000 --> 00:26:45,000
Henry Ford, in his true wit that he had many years ago,

302
00:26:45,000 --> 00:26:49,000
he was confronted with stockholders and news reporters and someone in the crowd said,

303
00:26:49,000 --> 00:26:52,000
you know, Mr. Ford, I know you're going to mass produce these things,

304
00:26:52,000 --> 00:26:54,000
but what are you going to do about the fuel?

305
00:26:54,000 --> 00:26:56,000
Where are you going to get the fuel for all these things?

306
00:26:56,000 --> 00:26:58,000
And he stopped for a second, he thought, and he said, you know,

307
00:26:58,000 --> 00:27:01,000
I'm not going to worry about that.

308
00:27:01,000 --> 00:27:04,000
We know that in fact that hydrogen is everywhere.

309
00:27:04,000 --> 00:27:09,000
As long as we build cost-effective pieces of equipment that generate electricity,

310
00:27:09,000 --> 00:27:13,000
then we're going to look to those other companies that create and develop hydrogen

311
00:27:13,000 --> 00:27:15,000
to be able to supply us.

312
00:27:23,000 --> 00:27:26,000
Cisco as an acronym stands for System and Services Company.

313
00:27:26,000 --> 00:27:29,000
We deal primarily with restaurants, schools, hospitals,

314
00:27:29,000 --> 00:27:32,000
anybody that's in the food service business.

315
00:27:32,000 --> 00:27:37,000
We use triple pallet jacks to move the groceries from our warehouse to the docks

316
00:27:37,000 --> 00:27:39,000
and they're powered traditionally by lead core batteries.

317
00:27:39,000 --> 00:27:44,000
The fuel cell that we use here in Grand Rapids was provided for us by Plug Power

318
00:27:44,000 --> 00:27:48,000
and they are used in place of batteries and the fuel cell itself

319
00:27:48,000 --> 00:27:53,000
provides a consistent level of power during its entire use of its fuel,

320
00:27:53,000 --> 00:27:57,000
which is different from our traditional batteries, which have a declining performance.

321
00:27:57,000 --> 00:28:01,000
As soon as you start using that battery, the power starts to decline

322
00:28:01,000 --> 00:28:06,000
and therefore the performance of the piece of equipment declines with the decreasing power.

323
00:28:06,000 --> 00:28:09,000
The traditional battery lasts anywhere from six to eight hours,

324
00:28:09,000 --> 00:28:13,000
depending on how new that battery is, as compared to a fuel cell

325
00:28:13,000 --> 00:28:16,000
which may last up to 14 hours per shift.

326
00:28:16,000 --> 00:28:19,000
Huge savings for us because we're not changing batteries,

327
00:28:19,000 --> 00:28:23,000
we're not recharging batteries so we have utility savings as well,

328
00:28:23,000 --> 00:28:28,000
but also our selectors stay busy selecting groceries instead of swapping batteries out.

329
00:28:28,000 --> 00:28:30,000
They're a very smooth operating source of power.

330
00:28:30,000 --> 00:28:33,000
We've had good results from a handling standpoint.

331
00:28:33,000 --> 00:28:38,000
The units themselves weigh 600 pounds less than our previous batteries

332
00:28:38,000 --> 00:28:42,000
and if you take the 600 pounds off, replace it with a new power cell,

333
00:28:42,000 --> 00:28:46,000
the handle which the selector operates becomes much easier to move around

334
00:28:46,000 --> 00:28:48,000
and that's been an added benefit.

335
00:28:48,000 --> 00:28:52,000
The employees that operate the triple pallet jacks have been positive

336
00:28:52,000 --> 00:28:56,000
in their feedback about how they operate, how smooth they operate

337
00:28:56,000 --> 00:28:59,000
and so far we've had no negative feedback from them,

338
00:28:59,000 --> 00:29:02,000
which is probably the most important vote of confidence.

339
00:29:02,000 --> 00:29:08,000
The people that actually use this day in, day out as part of their tools to do their job

340
00:29:08,000 --> 00:29:11,000
are enjoying the experience.

341
00:29:11,000 --> 00:29:17,000
The operators of these triple pallet jacks are responsible to fuel their unit when necessary.

342
00:29:17,000 --> 00:29:21,000
It operates much like a carb does in terms of a fuel gauge.

343
00:29:21,000 --> 00:29:23,000
When it does indicate it needs to be refueled,

344
00:29:23,000 --> 00:29:27,000
the selector comes to the fuel station and goes through a very quick process,

345
00:29:27,000 --> 00:29:33,000
usually less than a minute to refuel his or her particular triple pallet jack.

346
00:29:33,000 --> 00:29:38,000
There are warehouses using this technology to various degrees already.

347
00:29:38,000 --> 00:29:41,000
We're on the front end of this change.

348
00:29:41,000 --> 00:29:47,000
I'd like to think in the future this entire facility will be powered by an alternative fuel source

349
00:29:47,000 --> 00:29:52,000
and if Hydrogen's the answer, we're certainly one step forward in the right direction.

350
00:29:58,000 --> 00:30:01,000
Our customers are asking for better solutions.

351
00:30:01,000 --> 00:30:07,000
They want to be quieter, they want to be lighter, they want to be smarter machines.

352
00:30:09,000 --> 00:30:15,000
Many of our products that are used for golf environments are in a situation where

353
00:30:15,000 --> 00:30:17,000
they're used very early in the morning.

354
00:30:17,000 --> 00:30:22,000
A lot of golf courses are being built around houses and they want quiet equipment.

355
00:30:22,000 --> 00:30:28,000
Fuel cells are a solution for this.

356
00:30:28,000 --> 00:30:33,000
We don't want to have to sacrifice performance in order to get the benefits of electric power.

357
00:30:33,000 --> 00:30:38,000
So first of all, one of our guiding principles is that the machines will be able to do the same tasks

358
00:30:38,000 --> 00:30:42,000
that you're used to and feel and operate much the same way.

359
00:30:42,000 --> 00:30:45,000
Given that assumption, there are some differences.

360
00:30:45,000 --> 00:30:51,000
The components are different sized and different weights, so you have to repackage them in new areas.

361
00:30:51,000 --> 00:30:55,000
They have to be weather protected and environmental protected.

362
00:30:55,000 --> 00:30:57,000
They're basically off-road equipment.

363
00:30:59,000 --> 00:31:03,000
The fuel cells that we are using are called a PEM fuel cell.

364
00:31:03,000 --> 00:31:08,000
PEM stands for Proton Exchange Membrane and it's one of several types of fuel cells,

365
00:31:08,000 --> 00:31:14,000
particularly suitable for mobile applications because they're compact, lightweight,

366
00:31:14,000 --> 00:31:18,000
they start up fast and they follow loads very quickly.

367
00:31:18,000 --> 00:31:22,000
We've chosen to use compressed hydrogen as a fuel storage onboard.

368
00:31:22,000 --> 00:31:29,000
In order to get enough volume of hydrogen, we are operating at 5,000 psi tanks.

369
00:31:29,000 --> 00:31:33,000
Keep the tanks lightweight instead of a thick heavy-walled steel tank.

370
00:31:33,000 --> 00:31:35,000
We've got a composite tank.

371
00:31:35,000 --> 00:31:41,000
They're a bladder, either aluminum or some kind of plastic wrapped with threads to make the tank strong enough.

372
00:31:41,000 --> 00:31:47,000
We're able to get lightweight power and we can refuel quickly with the hydrogen

373
00:31:47,000 --> 00:31:52,000
and batteries that are heavy and they take a lot of time to recharge.

374
00:31:55,000 --> 00:31:58,000
Hydrogen in a fuel cell is clean.

375
00:31:58,000 --> 00:32:01,000
It is completely green and you give off water.

376
00:32:01,000 --> 00:32:06,000
There's a lot fewer moving parts than in an engine, a lot less friction.

377
00:32:06,000 --> 00:32:12,000
As the industry evolves, there's no reason it shouldn't be able to get long life as one of its better attributes.

378
00:32:12,000 --> 00:32:15,000
In my opinion, hydrogen is safe when used properly.

379
00:32:15,000 --> 00:32:19,000
Systems have to be designed so that they're safe, people have to be trained.

380
00:32:19,000 --> 00:32:22,000
Then it's just like handling any of these other high-energy contents.

381
00:32:22,000 --> 00:32:29,000
One of the key advantages that our industry has is that we are a fleet operation.

382
00:32:29,000 --> 00:32:35,000
Turf equipment on a golf course or a park system or something comes home the roost in the same building every night

383
00:32:35,000 --> 00:32:37,000
and then is deployed during the day and comes back.

384
00:32:37,000 --> 00:32:44,000
The ability to put in one central refueling site to take care of a bunch of product is inherent to our business.

385
00:32:44,000 --> 00:32:50,000
It lets us become, I think, a niche market that can start to use fuel cells quicker than many other places.

386
00:32:57,000 --> 00:32:59,000
We got started in 1980.

387
00:32:59,000 --> 00:33:02,000
We brewed our first batch of beer at a smaller facility.

388
00:33:02,000 --> 00:33:05,000
I was a home brewer who turned commercial brewer.

389
00:33:05,000 --> 00:33:09,000
We've got 450 employees, seventh or eighth largest breweries in the country.

390
00:33:09,000 --> 00:33:12,000
Distribution in every state.

391
00:33:12,000 --> 00:33:20,000
I wanted to be more energy independent and so we started looking at ways to both conserve energy and be more energy efficient.

392
00:33:20,000 --> 00:33:26,000
Actually, going back to when we first started, I put in things like ice banks to store energy at night.

393
00:33:26,000 --> 00:33:29,000
So we've been embracing some of those concepts for a long time.

394
00:33:29,000 --> 00:33:36,000
We've done a lot of optimization and put in current technology and some of those projects have two or three year payback.

395
00:33:36,000 --> 00:33:41,000
So it's not all done strictly for environmental benefit, but it's nice to get both.

396
00:33:41,000 --> 00:33:46,000
Some of the projects don't have great returns and so you really couldn't justify them strictly on a return on investment basis.

397
00:33:46,000 --> 00:33:50,000
And we do a lot of what we do because we think it's the right thing.

398
00:33:50,000 --> 00:34:00,000
And as a manufacturer, being in an industry that does utilize a lot of resources, we see it as one of our obligations to do our business in a sound manner

399
00:34:00,000 --> 00:34:05,000
and look for ways to minimize inputs and to minimize waste streams.

400
00:34:06,000 --> 00:34:12,000
As a manufacturer, power needs are 24-7 because we have refrigeration and pumps and things that are operating.

401
00:34:12,000 --> 00:34:20,000
It was both from energy efficiency and from air emissions, I guess, that I really wanted to give the fuel cell a try.

402
00:34:20,000 --> 00:34:26,000
We've got four 250 kilowatt units that are considered a direct fuel cell, so they don't need a separate source of hydrogen.

403
00:34:26,000 --> 00:34:31,000
They have an internal process that reforms the hydrogen out of the feed gas.

404
00:34:31,000 --> 00:34:37,000
So we feed it either biogas or natural gas and the process is part of the fuel cell stack.

405
00:34:37,000 --> 00:34:41,000
And so as the gas goes in, hydrogen gets separated and then that's fed into the fuel cell.

406
00:34:41,000 --> 00:34:43,000
We also have heat recovery boilers.

407
00:34:43,000 --> 00:34:50,000
We capture about a million and a quarter BTUs of energy back as steam and that goes back into our brewing process.

408
00:34:50,000 --> 00:34:57,000
The fuel cell is, I think, at the top as far as overall conversion of that input energy to output electricity.

409
00:34:57,000 --> 00:35:02,000
Having the distributed power generation, you're not losing power through transmission line loss.

410
00:35:02,000 --> 00:35:06,000
If you can co-generate and use the heat and the electricity, you've picked up even more.

411
00:35:06,000 --> 00:35:12,000
So I think our overall efficiency is approaching 70% for our input energy with the heat recovery,

412
00:35:12,000 --> 00:35:18,000
which would be close to double, I think, what the average fossil fuel plant would be putting out.

413
00:35:18,000 --> 00:35:24,000
As far as nitrogen oxides and sulfur dioxide and other things that are normal combustion byproducts,

414
00:35:24,000 --> 00:35:26,000
none of those that are emitted from the fuel cell.

415
00:35:26,000 --> 00:35:32,000
All of our fermenters are tied into pipes where we can collect the carbon dioxide that's naturally produced from fermentation.

416
00:35:32,000 --> 00:35:37,000
And that's compressed and cleaned up and stored and allows us to have our own source of CO2 here.

417
00:35:37,000 --> 00:35:40,000
Normally, breweries would purchase that if they don't recover it.

418
00:35:40,000 --> 00:35:46,000
And so now that we've recovered ours, we have our own source of naturally produced carbon dioxide that's been captured

419
00:35:46,000 --> 00:35:49,000
rather than emitted naturally produced carbon dioxide.

420
00:35:49,000 --> 00:35:53,000
It's used in the bottling process and moving beer around and dispensing beer.

421
00:35:53,000 --> 00:35:55,000
So we've just completed a pretty big solar array.

422
00:35:55,000 --> 00:35:57,000
I think we'll have one of the largest in the country.

423
00:35:57,000 --> 00:36:02,000
So that's pretty exciting and we're using sort of new inverter technology that's very efficient.

424
00:36:02,000 --> 00:36:05,000
So we're doing a good job converting sun's energy into electricity.

425
00:36:05,000 --> 00:36:07,000
Middle part of the day, we're drawing more power.

426
00:36:07,000 --> 00:36:13,000
So when our solar panels are putting out their maximum is when our power consumption is at its maximum as well.

427
00:36:13,000 --> 00:36:17,000
When the solar's not working, we have our fuel cells giving us our base load.

428
00:36:17,000 --> 00:36:19,000
So it's a good combination for us.

429
00:36:19,000 --> 00:36:21,000
We actually have our own herd of cattle.

430
00:36:21,000 --> 00:36:28,000
We feed our spent grain to the cattle and the manure from that is composted and put back on our hops field.

431
00:36:28,000 --> 00:36:31,000
So we have a fairly closed loop on our hops here on site.

432
00:36:31,000 --> 00:36:34,000
We do treat all of our own wastewater.

433
00:36:34,000 --> 00:36:40,000
So we take all of our waste streams, our liquid waste from the brewing process, spilled beer, yeast, bits of hops and malt.

434
00:36:40,000 --> 00:36:47,000
And that's fed into a digester which produces between 35 to 70 cubic feet a minute of methane.

435
00:36:47,000 --> 00:36:50,000
And then that methane is fed to the fuel cells.

436
00:36:50,000 --> 00:36:53,000
We use a mix of biogas and natural gas.

437
00:36:53,000 --> 00:36:56,000
Since it's more efficient, it'll be cheaper to produce power this way.

438
00:36:56,000 --> 00:37:02,000
Up to close to 80% of our own electrical power needs generated here on site.

439
00:37:02,000 --> 00:37:11,000
Our goal will be to get to 100% power generation and through both conservation efforts and some additional power generation, I think we can get there.

440
00:37:11,000 --> 00:37:13,000
I think it works for a lot of other industries.

441
00:37:13,000 --> 00:37:15,000
We get a lot of visitors here.

442
00:37:15,000 --> 00:37:20,000
I know there's quite a few hotels in one group that's put in fuel cells.

443
00:37:20,000 --> 00:37:22,000
One of the local casinos has put them in.

444
00:37:22,000 --> 00:37:28,000
So if you have a need for both heat and electricity on a continuous basis, you can justify this kind of technology.

445
00:37:34,000 --> 00:37:39,000
The California Fuel Cell Partnership is a collaboration amongst industry and government.

446
00:37:39,000 --> 00:37:48,000
We have members from the automotive industry, energy companies, fuel cell technology companies, as well as government from state, local and federal levels.

447
00:37:48,000 --> 00:37:53,000
We're working together to promote the commercialization of hydrogen-powered fuel cell vehicles.

448
00:37:55,000 --> 00:38:04,000
Many years ago when we were dealing with trying to reduce smog in the face of our continued population and vehicle growth here in California,

449
00:38:04,000 --> 00:38:09,000
we looked and said we really need to have zero emission vehicles or something that's very, very close.

450
00:38:09,000 --> 00:38:11,000
And there were two technologies available.

451
00:38:11,000 --> 00:38:14,000
One was battery electric vehicles.

452
00:38:14,000 --> 00:38:16,000
The other technology was fuel cell vehicles.

453
00:38:16,000 --> 00:38:20,000
With this particular vehicle, it actually has a hydrogen fuel cell system in it.

454
00:38:20,000 --> 00:38:23,000
And what that system is, we have high pressure hydrogen stored in the vehicle.

455
00:38:23,000 --> 00:38:28,000
This fuel cell itself actually converts this electrochemically to electricity, which drives the vehicle.

456
00:38:28,000 --> 00:38:31,000
What I tend to get comments about is the sound or lack of it.

457
00:38:31,000 --> 00:38:35,000
In this particular vehicle, this platform, we have a compressor, which makes a little bit of noise.

458
00:38:35,000 --> 00:38:38,000
But overall, it's about as quiet as it can be.

459
00:38:40,000 --> 00:38:44,000
When we first started this program, you know, we had a lot of vehicle issues and stuff like that.

460
00:38:44,000 --> 00:38:48,000
I have to say that we've definitely turned that around to where these vehicles are very reliable.

461
00:38:48,000 --> 00:38:51,000
We have them out in a fleet over the whole country.

462
00:38:51,000 --> 00:38:58,000
And we're very impressed with the way they perform and handle and their reliability.

463
00:38:59,000 --> 00:39:03,000
Oftentimes, I get comments about how stable it feels, how it doesn't feel like a prototype.

464
00:39:03,000 --> 00:39:06,000
It feels very much like a car that you could just go out and buy.

465
00:39:06,000 --> 00:39:09,000
And obviously, the next question I get is, why can't I get it now?

466
00:39:09,000 --> 00:39:13,000
The most common comment I see is that the vehicle is really cool.

467
00:39:13,000 --> 00:39:16,000
When you get in the vehicle and you drive around in general,

468
00:39:16,000 --> 00:39:20,000
there's not much of a difference between that vehicle and a conventional vehicle.

469
00:39:20,000 --> 00:39:25,000
It drives about the same, better pickup in the city, better acceleration, a little quieter.

470
00:39:25,000 --> 00:39:28,000
But when they know that it's boarding hydrogen and has a fuel cell,

471
00:39:28,000 --> 00:39:33,000
it has this cool green feel to it, and that's what people respond to.

472
00:39:34,000 --> 00:39:38,000
We have real-world customers, so we'll have real-world feedback.

473
00:39:38,000 --> 00:39:43,000
The customer can cope with infrastructure, with the vehicle durability, with the range issues.

474
00:39:43,000 --> 00:39:47,000
The customer compares the vehicle just to a normal, standard car.

475
00:39:47,000 --> 00:39:53,000
That's why we have custom operation because it's not only important to have technology advancement,

476
00:39:53,000 --> 00:39:56,000
but also to listen closely to what the customer says,

477
00:39:56,000 --> 00:40:01,000
because at the end of the day, if the customer does not buy your nice piece of technical equipment,

478
00:40:01,000 --> 00:40:03,000
the whole technology is a failure.

479
00:40:08,000 --> 00:40:13,000
With a battery-electric vehicle, you have to make the electricity somehow to recharge the batteries.

480
00:40:13,000 --> 00:40:16,000
With this vehicle, you have to make the hydrogen somehow.

481
00:40:17,000 --> 00:40:20,000
The hydrogen tanks are right under the rear seats.

482
00:40:20,000 --> 00:40:24,000
The fuel cell system is located under the front seats, the driver and passenger seats.

483
00:40:26,000 --> 00:40:31,000
The electric motor is up front, and then in the back, under the cargo compartment, there's a battery.

484
00:40:31,000 --> 00:40:35,000
And the battery works with the fuel cell to provide electricity to the electric motor.

485
00:40:35,000 --> 00:40:39,000
The battery does the same thing that it does in a hybrid car, which is called regenerative braking.

486
00:40:39,000 --> 00:40:44,000
And what happens is when we're slowing down, the energy that otherwise would have just been wasted through the brakes

487
00:40:44,000 --> 00:40:49,000
is actually captured in the battery, and then when you need power to accelerate or go up a hill,

488
00:40:49,000 --> 00:40:53,000
both the battery and the fuel cell can put electric power to the electric motors.

489
00:40:55,000 --> 00:40:58,000
This vehicle is equipped with leak detectors that will immediately tell you if there's a leak,

490
00:40:58,000 --> 00:41:01,000
so you know to pull over, get the vehicle towed to a place that could be repaired.

491
00:41:01,000 --> 00:41:06,000
Hydrogen is very, very light, so if there is a leak, it tends to disperse very rapidly.

492
00:41:06,000 --> 00:41:12,000
The hydrogen storage tanks in these vehicles are incredibly well-designed, very strong, fiber-wrapped cylinders.

493
00:41:12,000 --> 00:41:16,000
They've done extensive testing with them to ensure that they're as safe as possible.

494
00:41:16,000 --> 00:41:22,000
It has a neat safety feature where there's some little side pillars in the rear of the vehicle, you can see.

495
00:41:22,000 --> 00:41:26,000
And there's tubes running up from the hydrogen tanks through those side pillars up to a pressure release valve,

496
00:41:26,000 --> 00:41:28,000
which is a little bump you see on the roof of the car.

497
00:41:28,000 --> 00:41:31,000
So if there's an accident, the system will detect a loss of pressure,

498
00:41:31,000 --> 00:41:35,000
and the hydrogen will be immediately vented through the pressure release valve on the roof.

499
00:41:35,000 --> 00:41:39,000
You can measure hydrogen in terms of volume. You can talk about gallons or liters of hydrogen.

500
00:41:39,000 --> 00:41:43,000
But because the volume changes at different pressures, we tend to think of it in terms of weight.

501
00:41:43,000 --> 00:41:47,000
A certain amount of hydrogen is going to weigh the same regardless of what pressure it's at.

502
00:41:47,000 --> 00:41:51,000
One kilogram of hydrogen stores as much energy as one gallon of gasoline.

503
00:41:51,000 --> 00:41:54,000
This vehicle stores about two kilograms of hydrogen.

504
00:41:54,000 --> 00:42:00,000
Because it's under high pressure, that pump, when I clamped the nozzle onto the gas tank, it has to form a very tight seal.

505
00:42:00,000 --> 00:42:04,000
And unless the pump knows that there's a very tight seal, the pump won't even turn on.

506
00:42:04,000 --> 00:42:07,000
So it's got a lot of safety built into it.

507
00:42:07,000 --> 00:42:11,000
Right now, we're at a very interesting stage of development of this technology.

508
00:42:11,000 --> 00:42:16,000
In some ways, fuel cells are an easier fit for buses than they are for cars.

509
00:42:16,000 --> 00:42:19,000
You don't get much cleaner than a fuel cell bus, that's for sure.

510
00:42:19,000 --> 00:42:21,000
It's a zero-emission vehicle.

511
00:42:21,000 --> 00:42:27,000
We're the first to actually build a fleet of fuel cell buses for an actual heavy-duty transit application.

512
00:42:27,000 --> 00:42:32,000
New Flyer Industries is the largest manufacturer in North America of heavy-duty transit vehicles.

513
00:42:32,000 --> 00:42:40,000
Currently have about 17,000 buses on the road at almost 250 different transit agencies.

514
00:42:40,000 --> 00:42:50,000
Because of the fact that we had the Vancouver Winter Olympics, there was a drive to showcase and demonstrate green technology.

515
00:42:50,000 --> 00:42:56,000
When the contract was originally tendered to do the fuel cell buses for the Olympics,

516
00:42:56,000 --> 00:43:02,000
we proceeded to develop an initial prototype, which would eventually serve as the mold for our production.

517
00:43:02,000 --> 00:43:09,000
One of the big challenges with developing a fuel cell bus is to make sure that it can operate in the cold temperature environment.

518
00:43:09,000 --> 00:43:18,000
Once we were satisfied with that, then we proceeded with the production to build the 20 buses for the Vancouver 2010 Olympics.

519
00:43:18,000 --> 00:43:25,000
In most ways, the vehicle went through our standard production line, our standard production stations.

520
00:43:25,000 --> 00:43:29,000
The only difference was that there were a few extra steps at certain points in the line,

521
00:43:29,000 --> 00:43:33,000
where we had to install the fuel tanks and some of the other hybrid components,

522
00:43:33,000 --> 00:43:38,000
but we were able to incorporate that all within our existing processes and equipment.

523
00:43:38,000 --> 00:43:47,000
Because we're a low-floor design, which all our buses are nowadays for wheelchair accessibility and ease of getting on and off for passengers,

524
00:43:47,000 --> 00:43:51,000
one of the challenges with that is that the bus is very low to the ground,

525
00:43:51,000 --> 00:43:54,000
so there's no room under the bus to really install much equipment.

526
00:43:54,000 --> 00:44:03,000
With the large number of components that are required for the fuel cell bus in terms of the hydrogen tanks, the batteries, the cooling systems,

527
00:44:03,000 --> 00:44:09,000
all that takes up a lot of space. We ended up putting quite a few of the components on the roof of the vehicle,

528
00:44:09,000 --> 00:44:11,000
as well as in the rear engine compartment.

529
00:44:11,000 --> 00:44:19,000
From a static standpoint, you would actually have a lot of trouble just from a quick glance telling a fuel cell bus apart from a regular bus.

530
00:44:19,000 --> 00:44:23,000
If you were to walk on and sit in a seat, you wouldn't notice much out of the ordinary

531
00:44:23,000 --> 00:44:26,000
and the stuff you don't see, which makes the technology interesting.

532
00:44:26,000 --> 00:44:30,000
The big challenge is operating a hydrogen fuel cell coach in cold weather.

533
00:44:30,000 --> 00:44:34,000
The primary byproduct of the chemical reaction is water.

534
00:44:34,000 --> 00:44:39,000
Of course, we run into the issue of what happens when you drop below zero degrees Celsius.

535
00:44:39,000 --> 00:44:43,000
If you don't design for that, you can certainly run the risk of freezing that water,

536
00:44:43,000 --> 00:44:46,000
which can definitely damage portions of your fuel cell.

537
00:44:46,000 --> 00:44:54,000
One of the initial things we had to work on was a way to plug in the vehicles overnight to ensure that the fuel cell didn't freeze.

538
00:44:54,000 --> 00:44:59,000
The other big challenge is how do you ensure that on those cold days that you have enough heat available

539
00:44:59,000 --> 00:45:03,000
so that you can properly start the bus and then once the bus is running,

540
00:45:03,000 --> 00:45:08,000
how do you ensure that you have enough heat available so that everybody is comfortable within the vehicle.

541
00:45:08,000 --> 00:45:15,000
One of the aspects about the fuel cell bus design is that it uses electric motors to drive the wheels.

542
00:45:15,000 --> 00:45:19,000
The fuel cell itself does not actually directly drive the vehicle.

543
00:45:19,000 --> 00:45:22,000
All it does is convert hydrogen to electricity.

544
00:45:22,000 --> 00:45:27,000
So that electricity is used to drive motors and other systems on the vehicle.

545
00:45:27,000 --> 00:45:33,000
One of the advantages of an electric motor is that at very low speeds they generate a high amount of torque.

546
00:45:33,000 --> 00:45:35,000
The acceleration is very good.

547
00:45:35,000 --> 00:45:40,000
The other big advantage is the braking because we have an electric system on the bus

548
00:45:40,000 --> 00:45:43,000
with very powerful storage batteries and generators.

549
00:45:43,000 --> 00:45:49,000
We're able to regain energy from the braking system when the vehicle stops.

550
00:45:49,000 --> 00:45:54,000
And not only does that increase the life of your brake pads and allow you to charge up your electrical system,

551
00:45:54,000 --> 00:45:57,000
but it also gives you a lot of stopping power.

552
00:45:59,000 --> 00:46:05,000
Hydrogen buses are designed to work very similar to the way the diesel bus is as far as duty cycle,

553
00:46:05,000 --> 00:46:09,000
and they're able to perform all the same functions as a standard diesel bus.

554
00:46:09,000 --> 00:46:14,000
Our buses have a range of about 300 to 325 miles.

555
00:46:14,000 --> 00:46:17,000
Diesel buses, and again this fuel cell bus,

556
00:46:17,000 --> 00:46:21,000
dependent on a route service, it can be out from anywhere from a trip or run,

557
00:46:21,000 --> 00:46:26,000
which is just a few hours up to 16, 17, even 18 hours without any trouble.

558
00:46:26,000 --> 00:46:34,000
These buses, because of extra infrastructure on the roof for gas, storage, for all the additional components,

559
00:46:34,000 --> 00:46:39,000
they're over 8,000 pounds heavier than the comparable diesel bus.

560
00:46:39,000 --> 00:46:46,000
But in spite of that, we're seeing as much as 100% or double the fuel economy over a diesel bus.

561
00:46:46,000 --> 00:46:54,000
The main thing everybody notices is how quiet and smooth that the vehicle is in comparison to a standard diesel bus.

562
00:46:54,000 --> 00:46:59,000
There's no transmission on it, so it's very smooth, powers away very quietly.

563
00:46:59,000 --> 00:47:04,000
We have had some comments from riders that the bus is actually too quiet.

564
00:47:04,000 --> 00:47:06,000
You can actually sneak up on them.

565
00:47:06,000 --> 00:47:10,000
They've been surprised when it pulls up to the curb, and they didn't even realize it was there.

566
00:47:11,000 --> 00:47:18,000
With the fuel cell technology, this bus doesn't care where the hydrogen comes from,

567
00:47:18,000 --> 00:47:26,000
and the value of hydrogen in transportation applications is that we can make hydrogen from solar and wind and biomass.

568
00:47:26,000 --> 00:47:29,000
Here we're using natural gas.

569
00:47:29,000 --> 00:47:34,000
While it's not completely zero emission, it has some CO2 emissions.

570
00:47:34,000 --> 00:47:39,000
Well to wheel, it's still better than our regular diesel internal combustion engine vehicles.

571
00:47:39,000 --> 00:47:43,000
They're basically a large golf cart, and there's not a lot of maintenance on a golf cart.

572
00:47:43,000 --> 00:47:50,000
One of the largest maintenance items for any bus is the brakes, and with these vehicles having regenerative braking,

573
00:47:50,000 --> 00:47:55,000
we're hoping to realize better brake life than the cost savings associated with that.

574
00:47:55,000 --> 00:47:57,000
We're learning from these buses.

575
00:47:57,000 --> 00:47:59,000
We're learning from other examples throughout the world.

576
00:47:59,000 --> 00:48:06,000
All the supercomputers of the world, all the brilliant minds that delivered the technology in the first place,

577
00:48:06,000 --> 00:48:15,000
can't think of every variable, and what we do here is we capture almost all the variables that they can't think of.

578
00:48:15,000 --> 00:48:24,000
And we're all learning from this, not just us as users, but the technology providers are seeing things that they couldn't replicate in the labs.

579
00:48:24,000 --> 00:48:31,000
We're very much committed to looking at alternative fuels to improve our environmental footprint.

580
00:48:31,000 --> 00:48:36,000
Zero emission from the tailpipe, virtually no noise from the engine,

581
00:48:36,000 --> 00:48:45,000
and the potential of addressing global warming, climate change issues, sustainable energy supplies to fuel our vehicles,

582
00:48:45,000 --> 00:48:47,000
to help us reach energy independence.

583
00:48:47,000 --> 00:48:58,000
Our end state goal is commercialization so that all of the transit buses in the United States we would like to see as zero emission fuel cell buses.

584
00:48:59,000 --> 00:49:04,000
Hydrogen has been used safely throughout our economy.

585
00:49:04,000 --> 00:49:11,000
We use most of the hydrogen today to make cleaner gasoline, but it's also used in food manufacturing and consumer products.

586
00:49:11,000 --> 00:49:17,000
If you look at hydrogen compared to gasoline, certainly both fuels have a lot of energy content.

587
00:49:17,000 --> 00:49:22,000
You must pay attention to safety considerations when using the fuel.

588
00:49:22,000 --> 00:49:26,000
Hydrogen is no less safe than gasoline, it's just different.

589
00:49:26,000 --> 00:49:33,000
If there is a hydrogen leak, it's very light and so it will go up and rise immediately and dissipate into the atmosphere.

590
00:49:33,000 --> 00:49:40,000
It's totally non-toxic, it won't cause health problems or environmental problems if it is released into the atmosphere.

591
00:49:40,000 --> 00:49:44,000
All vehicle fuels can be dangerous.

592
00:49:44,000 --> 00:49:47,000
If they weren't, they wouldn't be useful as fuel.

593
00:49:48,000 --> 00:49:55,000
The trick for any fuel is to engineer it so that it is as safe as currently available technologies.

594
00:49:55,000 --> 00:49:58,000
Today that's gasoline in conventional vehicles.

595
00:49:58,000 --> 00:50:07,000
And most people I know working with hydrogen believe that hydrogen is either as safe or safer than gasoline is today.

596
00:50:07,000 --> 00:50:09,000
It is safer than gasoline.

597
00:50:09,000 --> 00:50:17,000
Most people say today that if you were to have a gasoline engine today and you were trying to bring it on the market for the very first time,

598
00:50:17,000 --> 00:50:22,000
there would be no way that you would be able to put that gasoline engine onto the marketplace.

599
00:50:22,000 --> 00:50:23,000
It just wouldn't happen.

600
00:50:23,000 --> 00:50:34,000
I quite sincerely believe and I've seen test evidence that supports my conclusion that the gas tank in the suburban that I drive is more dangerous than a hydrogen fuel tank.

601
00:50:34,000 --> 00:50:39,000
We have conducted 120,000 fuelings worldwide already.

602
00:50:39,000 --> 00:50:47,000
We know hydrogen can be delivered, compressed and dispensed into vehicles very safely, as safely if not more safely than traditional fuels.

603
00:50:47,000 --> 00:50:51,000
We've done extensive safety training with our maintenance and service personnel.

604
00:50:51,000 --> 00:51:00,000
We've worked with some very good partners that have designed some very good systems, our fueling station, our facility upgrades,

605
00:51:00,000 --> 00:51:09,000
all incorporate hydrogen sensors and fire sensors and very robust systems to track that.

606
00:51:09,000 --> 00:51:11,000
Safety was a big part of it.

607
00:51:11,000 --> 00:51:19,000
I wanted to make sure that the testing that they had done was adequate for our employees' benefit as well as for the community.

608
00:51:19,000 --> 00:51:25,000
I am good fortune to drive a fuel cell car on a regular basis and I use it to take my kids to school,

609
00:51:25,000 --> 00:51:29,000
go to the baseball practice, go grocery shopping, come to work.

610
00:51:29,000 --> 00:51:33,000
When they fuel the car, there's no fumes or drips of gasoline.

611
00:51:33,000 --> 00:51:36,000
I'd much rather drive my fuel cell vehicle than my gasoline vehicle.

